explanation: Food allergies can cause a wide range of symptoms, including vomiting, nasal congestion, abdominal cramps, and angioedema. This is due to the bodys immune system overreacting to a particular food protein.}, {diagnosis: Drug allergy
explanation: Similar to food allergies, drug allergies can also trigger these symptoms as an immune response to a specific medication.}, {diagnosis: Viral gastroenteritis (Stomach flu)

explanation: This common infection often presents with vomiting, abdominal cramps, and sometimes nasal congestion. While less common, angioedema can occur in severe cases.}, {diagnosis: Acute sinusitis

explanation: Sinus infections can cause nasal congestion and facial pain, which may radiate to the jaw and feel like abdominal cramps. Vomiting can occur due to mucus buildup and post-nasal drip. Angioedema is less common but possible.}, {diagnosis: Anaphylaxis

explanation: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction, anaphylaxis can cause all the listed symptoms. It requires immediate medical attention.}, {diagnosis: Hereditary angioedema (HAE)

explanation: A rare genetic condition, HAE causes recurrent episodes of swelling, including angioedema. It may be accompanied by abdominal pain, vomiting, and occasionally nasal congestion.}, {diagnosis: Appendicitis

explanation: While primarily associated with right lower abdominal pain, appendicitis can initially present with more general symptoms like vomiting, abdominal cramps, and loss of appetite. Nasal congestion and angioedema are less likely.}, {diagnosis: Migraine
explanation: While primarily a headache disorder, migraines can cause nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain. Nasal congestion and angioedema are uncommon but possible.}, {diagnosis: Panic attack

explanation: Extreme anxiety and stress can lead to physical symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, abdominal discomfort, and difficulty breathing. While less common, nasal congestion and even angioedema can occur.}, {diagnosis: Superior mesenteric artery syndrome (SMAS)

explanation: This rare digestive disorder occurs when the duodenum (part of the small intestine) is compressed. It can cause vomiting, abdominal pain after eating, and weight loss. Nasal congestion and angioedema are not typically associated.}
